<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-08-04T21:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-08-04T21:00:00-05:00" n="588" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d588">
                    <note rend="inline" type="source">811.20 Defense (M)/14088a: Telegram</note>
                    <head>
                        <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            Chargé in China</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Atcheson</hi></persName>)</head>
                    <opener>
                        <dateline rendition="#right">
                            <placeName>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-08-04T22:00:00-04:00">August 4,
                                1943—10 p.m.</date>
                        </dateline>
                    </opener>
                    <p>1033. WPB<note n="19" xml:id="d588fn19">War Production Board.</note> wishes
                        following information. Should we continue to give priority to Russian owned
                        mercury and tin on American planes and if so what is best estimate as to
                        amounts available monthly. Mercury now has A–1 priority and present schedule
                        80,000 pounds monthly: tin has A–2 with monthly schedule 1,500,000
                        pounds.</p>
                    <closer>
                        <signed>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                        </signed>
                    </closer>
                </div>
                </body></text></TEI>